{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522134"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:41:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:41:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13808"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13808","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13808"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.14,0.69,0.06,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6425"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53842"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6425","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6425"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13808"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39304"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"2546"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12673"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16003"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53842","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53842"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of a painless swelling on the left side of his neck. He reports no other symptoms. He has a medical history of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease. His regular medication is omeprazole. He is an ex-smoker with a 30 pack-year history. On examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. There is a 3 cm firm, non-tender, fixed mass in the left supraclavicular region. The rest of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of the swelling?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Branchial cyst","Lymphoma","Metastatic oesophageal adenocarcinoma","Epidermoid cyst","Cystic hygroma"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely cause of the swelling in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Emetastatic oesophageal adenocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient\u0027s age, history of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease, and smoking history are risk factors for oesophageal cancer. The presence of a firm, fixed mass in the left supraclavicular region (Virchow\u0027s node) is highly suspicious for metastatic disease, particularly from the thorax or abdomen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ebranchial cyst\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents in younger individuals and is usually located along the anterior border of the sternocleidomastoid muscle, not in the supraclavicular region. It would also be more likely to be mobile and fluctuant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymphoma\u003C/strong\u003E can present with cervical lymphadenopathy, but it typically involves multiple lymph nodes and is often accompanied by systemic symptoms such as fever, night sweats, and weight loss, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eepidermoid cyst\u003C/strong\u003E is a benign, slow-growing cyst that develops from ectodermal tissue. It typically presents as a small, round bump under the skin, often on the face, neck, or trunk. It would not be fixed to underlying structures and is unlikely to reach 3 cm in size over just two weeks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecystic hygroma\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as a lymphangioma, is a congenital malformation of the lymphatic system. It typically presents at birth or in early childhood as a soft, compressible mass, most commonly in the neck or axilla. It would be extremely unusual for this to present for the first time in a 65-year-old man.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the patient\u0027s risk factors and the characteristics of the mass, metastatic oesophageal adenocarcinoma is the most likely diagnosis. The next steps in management would include urgent referral for further investigations, including imaging (CT or PET-CT) and biopsy of the mass. If confirmed, staging investigations and multidisciplinary team discussion would guide further treatment options.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Cervical lymphadenopathy can be the first presenting sign of oesophageal adenocarcinoma.","Metastatic spread to cervical lymph nodes is common in oesophageal cancer, particularly for tumors in the upper and middle thirds of the oesophagus.","A firm, fixed mass in the left supraclavicular region (Virchow\u0027s node) is highly suspicious for metastatic disease from the thorax or abdomen."],"references":["Aghedo BO, Kasi A. Virchow Node. [Updated 2022 Sep 26]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39304"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13808"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20751"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20751","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20751"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0G3Un2VsoB5VEnrQzLzsLxv8mWIIxd.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0G3Un2VsoB5VEnrQzLzsLxv8mWIIxd.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":768,"height":1024}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39304","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39304"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-27T10:39:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-27T10:41:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6425"}},"content":{"data":{"type":